menu "SPI NAND Flash configuration"

    choice SPI_NAND_FLASH_WL_IMPL
        prompt "Wear Leveling Implementation"
        default SPI_NAND_FLASH_WL_DHARA
        help
            Select the wear leveling / FTL (Flash Translation Layer) implementation for SPI NAND flash.

            - Dhara: Mature, proven implementation with good performance. Default choice for most applications.
            - nvblock: Newer implementation with smaller memory footprint and configurable block sizes.
              Suitable for resource-constrained systems. Currently experimental.

            WARNING: Changing wear leveling implementation requires erasing the entire flash chip.
            Data formats are not compatible between implementations.

    config SPI_NAND_FLASH_WL_DHARA
        bool "Dhara (default, recommended)"
        help
            Use Dhara library for wear leveling.

            Dhara is a mature and well-tested Flash Translation Layer implementation that provides:
            - Excellent wear leveling performance
            - Proven stability in production environments
            - Good documentation and community support

            This is the default and recommended option for most use cases.

    config SPI_NAND_FLASH_WL_NVBLOCK
        bool "nvblock (experimental, smaller footprint)"
        help
            Use nvblock library for wear leveling.

            nvblock is a lightweight Flash Translation Layer implementation that provides:
            - Smaller memory footprint (configurable block sizes down to 64 bytes)
            - Simpler, more maintainable codebase
            - Flexible block grouping for different use cases
            - Atomic write guarantees with power-fail recovery

            This option is suitable for:
            - Resource-constrained systems with limited RAM
            - Applications requiring specific block size configurations
            - Systems prioritizing small code size

            Note: nvblock integration is currently EXPERIMENTAL. Thorough testing
            is recommended before using in production.

    endchoice

    config NAND_FLASH_VERIFY_WRITE
        bool "Verify SPI NAND flash writes"
        default n
        help
            If this option is enabled, any time SPI NAND flash is written then the data will be read
            back and verified. This can catch hardware problems with SPI NAND flash, or flash which
            was not erased before verification.

    config NAND_FLASH_ENABLE_BDL
        bool "Enable Block Device Layer (BDL) support"
        depends on IDF_INIT_VERSION >= "6.0"
        default n
        help
            Enable Block Device Layer (BDL) support for SPI NAND Flash. This provides:
            - Standard esp_blockdev_t interface for layered architecture
            - Flash Block Device Layer (raw NAND flash access)
            - Wear-Leveling Block Device Layer (logical sector access with wear leveling)
            - Advanced layered API (spi_nand_flash_init_with_layers)
            When disabled, only the legacy API is available.
            When enabled, the legacy spi_nand_flash_init_device() is not available (returns
            ESP_ERR_NOT_SUPPORTED). Use spi_nand_flash_init_with_layers().

            Note: This option requires ESP-IDF >= 6.0 (esp_blockdev component).
            Enabling this on ESP-IDF < 6.0 will result in a build error.

    config NAND_ENABLE_STATS
        bool "Host test statistics enabled"
        depends on IDF_TARGET_LINUX
        default n
        help
            This option enables gathering host test statistics and SPI NAND flash wear levelling simulation.

endmenu
